<dl id="n55009g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n55" href="#n55009g">N55 (VI.X.5)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n55all.htm#n55009g"> 9(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Stourbridge clay <small>color t.b.a.</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n55009g"><li>FW 184.12 </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/lexg.htm#n55009g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/g/l39g.htm#n55009g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n55009g">MS BL 47476a-2</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:527 <a name="gd11" href="../../ff/fdra/gda.htm#gd11">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/g/gd11.htm#n55009g">Draft: I.7&sect;1.11</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Powder a little coal and put it into the bowl of a common long tobacco-pipe; then cover the top well with a stopper of moist clay (made by mixing the powdered <mark>Stourbridge clay</mark> with a little water), and let the clay dry well. After it is well dried, fasten the bowl of the pipe over the flame of the gas-lamp. <small> H. E. Roscoe, <a name="HERC2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#HERC2"><cite title="source">Science Primer: Chemistry</cite></a> (n.d.) 66</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
